Value.value: This looks liked the caved-in entrance to what must have been a large city. Spider- and web-themed decorations cover the pillars.

This is the old caved-in entrance to Udos Dro'xun, an old Drow City underneath Amia Island. The Lolth-ruled city somewhat famously did trade dealings with Cordor, it's closest neighbor, for surface goods.

This is the old caved-in entrance to Udos Dro'xun, an old Drow City underneath Amia Island. The Lolth-ruled city somewhat famously had trade dealings with Cordor, its closest neighbor, for surface goods, even letting surfacers walk around freely if they brought food and water. Udos pre-dates Ultrinnan, the second Drow City to be built in the Amian Localdark by a good many years. While Udos Drox'un was destroyed by a coalition of Underdark monsters in 1369 DR, it wasn't until 1372, when the "Great Quake" of Cordor changed the subterranean architecture of the area, flooding the ruins and much of the surrounding area.

Value.value: This is a massive, overgrown section of mushrooms of a great many sizes and varieties.

Many Underdark cultures grow mushroom and fugnus farms for steady food, and Udos Dro'xun was no exception. This looks like a fungus plantation that "returned to earth" and sprawled out after Udos was destroyed. Cordor often traded with Udos Dro'xun for foodstuffs.

Many Underdark cultures grow mushroom and fungus farms for steady food, and Udos Dro'xun was no exception. This looks like a fungus plantation that "returned to earth" and sprawled out after Udos was destroyed. Udos' fungus farms were, in the early days, not enough to support the city, leading to a strange but healthy trade with Cordor, allowing many surface goods to enter a normally locked off area. When Udos was destroyed, many Drow fled to the surface to escape, and were temporarily granted Asylum by Cordor before popular demand, and internal tensions, forced them out.
These crystals run the range from brown to grey to black, and other various neutral colors.
Udos Dro'xun was known for its crystal and latticework, and such was often found even on the surface of Amia, since Udos Dro'xun was nearby. You can see similar work in the massive pillars nearby.

Udos Dro'xun was known for its crystal and latticework, and such was often found even on the surface of Amia, since Udos Dro'xun was nearby. You can see similar work in the massive pillars nearby - the drow used it extensively, since the crystal was stout and held up extremely well to pressure. In some cases, it was magically enchantable, as well. With recent cave shifts and changes, new untapped ores have been found, and just recently, new Deep Crystal and other ores have been found again in the area, more than a decade and a half after the destruction of Udos.
